        "description": [{
                "type": "text",
                "content": "In Japan, there is a <a href=\"https://www.nippon.com/en/features/h00124/\">traditional calendar</a> that splits the year into 24 seasons, called <i>sekki,</i> which are each then subdivided by 3 microseasons called <i>kō.</i> Each sekki and kō has a name that aligns with the characteristics of nature around the time. For example, March 11 falls under the sekki <i>\"insects awaken\"</i> and kō <i>\"first peach blossoms\"</i>."
            },
            {
                "type": "text",
                "content": "I created a website that displays my interpretation of the microseasons calendar. It displays all of the sekki and kō, in their original characters, at once in a relaxedly spinning ring, while the current seasons are highlighted in red."
            },
